I’ve spent my career helping founders, entrepreneurs, and pastors move from “I just need to not run out of money” 𝐭𝐨 𝐜𝐥𝐞𝐚𝐫, 𝐦𝐞𝐚𝐬𝐮𝐫𝐚𝐛𝐥𝐞, 𝐫𝐞𝐩𝐞𝐚𝐭𝐚𝐛𝐥𝐞 𝐟𝐢𝐧𝐚𝐧𝐜𝐢𝐚𝐥 𝐝𝐢𝐬𝐜𝐢𝐩𝐥𝐢𝐧𝐞.

What I’m seeing — in both businesses and parishes — is the same pattern: leaders know what they don’t know, but they don’t know what to ask. They rely on clichés instead of systems. They inherit complexity instead of building clarity.

So I’m starting a series focused on 𝐜𝐫𝐚𝐰𝐥 → 𝐰𝐚𝐥𝐤 → 𝐫𝐮𝐧 financial leadership for small organizations:

𝐂𝐫𝐚𝐰𝐥: weekly bank recs, one reporting format, one control per process.
𝐖𝐚𝐥𝐤: monthly close calendars, variance analysis, basic pricing discipline.
𝐑𝐮𝐧: rolling forecasts, scenario planning, exit readiness.

The goal isn’t to turn founders or pastors into accountants. It’s to help them know enough to ask the right questions — the ones that reveal whether their operations are stable, scalable, and stewarded well.

If you lead a small business, nonprofit, or parish and want to build financial clarity without complexity, this series is for you.
